In addition to antigens, blood types also have antibodies that attack cells with different antigens. For example, a person with type A blood has anti-B antibodies, while a person with type B blood has anti-A antibodies. A person with type AB blood has no antibodies, while a person with type O blood has both anti-A and anti-B antibodies. Blood types also play a role in pregnancy and can impact a mother's ability to carry a child with a different blood type.
